We’ve all been there—you finally finish painting a room, stand back to admire your work, and then stare at the leftover paint wondering, “What now?” Toss it? Definitely not. Keep it? Absolutely. But shove it into the garage to collect cobwebs and dry out? Nope, there's a better way.
If you’ve ever gone to touch up a scuff on the wall months later and opened a can of lumpy, dried-up goop, this one's for you. Here’s how to store leftover paint the right way—so it's actually usable when you need it again.
Step 1: Transfer It to a Smaller Container
Let’s be honest—most of us don’t leave behind half a can of paint. It’s more like a cup or two, max. And that giant can with all that air inside? That’s a fast track to dried-out paint.
Instead, pour the leftover paint into a smaller, airtight container. Mason jars, plastic screw-top containers, or even old salsa jars (cleaned out, of course) work great. Less air means your paint lasts longer.
Pro tip: Label the jar with the paint color, brand, room it was used in, and the date. You will forget what “Eggshell #3049” looks like in six months. Trust.
Step 2: Seal It Tight (Seriously, Tight)
If you're keeping it in the original can, clean the rim before you put the lid back on. Dried paint on the edge can mess with the seal and let in air. Tap the lid back on with a rubber mallet—not a hammer. A hammer can bend the lid and ruin the seal. No one wants to open a can and find a crusty pancake of paint.
Step 3: Store It Somewhere Cool and Dry
The garage might seem like a good spot, but if it gets too hot or cold, your paint will go bad faster than that forgotten takeout in your fridge. Aim for a cool, dry place inside your house—like a closet, utility room, or even under the sink if there's space.
Just make sure it’s out of reach of curious kids and pets. (Because let’s face it, paint is not snack-safe.)
Step 4: Stir Before You Touch Up
Paint separates as it sits. When you open it back up, it might look like a weird paint soup. That’s totally normal. Give it a good stir with a paint stick or even a disposable chopstick, and you’re back in business.
If it smells funky (think sour milk vibes) or has a chunky, rubbery texture that won’t mix back in—time to say goodbye. That paint is past its prime.
Bonus Tip: Keep a Paint Log
This one’s for the Type A folks—or those who just want to avoid guessing games in the future. Keep a note in your phone or a small notebook that lists the paint colors and finishes you’ve used in each room. When it’s time for a touch-up or repaint, you’ll have all the info right there. No need to go color-matching with a mystery flake at the hardware store.
Final Thought:
A little paint can go a long way—if you store it right. With just a few simple steps, you’ll save yourself the frustration (and money) of rebuying a gallon for a two-inch scratch. Your future self—and your walls—will thank you.

